%U A395717 914760,914760,914760,12899880,12899880,12899880,12899880,15768900,21635460,21635460,21635460,21635460
%N A395717 a(n) is the maximal number achievable by taking any sequence of positive integers less than or equal to n: s(1), s(2), s(3)... and generating a new sequence T with t(1) = s(1) and t(k+1) being the multiple of s(k+1) closest to t(k). In case there are two multiples of s(k+1) equally close, the sequence T is undefined. a(n) = maximal element of any sequence, T.
%C A395717 It is not possible to exceed half the lowest common multiple of the numbers used in S, except if the lowest common multiple is an element of S.
%C A395717 A great sequence to explore multiplication with elementary school children.
%C A395717 Terms can be found by using a greedy search; find the largest t(k+1) possible to reach from t(k) until no new numbers are found.
%e A395717 a(5) = 6 because of the sequence S={5,3}. T={5,3*2}={5,6}.
%e A395717 a(7) = 21 because the sequence S={7,4,5,6,7,5,4,6,7} generates T={7,4*2,5*2,6*2,7*2,5*3,4*4,6*3,7*3}={7,8,10,12,14,15,16,18,21}. The highest term in T is 21. No other sequence, S, produces a higher number than 21.
%e A395717 a(10) is at least 16 because S={10,6,7,8,5} generates T={10,12,14,16,15}. The highest term in T is 16. This is far from optimal. There is a different sequence S that gives a(10)=72.
%o A395717 (PARI) a(n) = {my(c, res); c = n; res = 1; while(c > 0, res = c; c = maxnext(c, n)); res}
%o A395717 maxnext(c, n) = {my(res = 0, besti = 0); for(i = 2, n, minp = (c\i)*i; maxp = minp + i; if(maxp - c < c - minp, if(maxp > res, res = maxp; besti = i))); res} \\ _David A. Corneth_, Jun 01 2026
%Y A395717 Cf. A003418.
%Y A395717 A395863 is the minimal number of integers in a sequence S so that T includes the maximal value a(n).
%Y A395717 A394181 is a related construction.
%K A395717 nonn
